<div class="content">
  <h2>6 Essential Pizza Dough Recipes</h2>

  <div class="recipe-section">
    <div class="recipe-header">
      <h3>1. New York Style</h3>
      <span class="recipe-meta">Bake: 500°F - 550°F | Hydration: ~62%</span>
    </div>
    <p>The iconic foldable slice. Crispy on the bottom, chewy on top, and sturdy enough to hold toppings. Uses olive oil and sugar for browning in home ovens.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Ingredients:</strong> High-gluten flour (or bread flour), water, active dry yeast, salt, sugar, olive oil.</li>
      <li><strong>Technique:</strong> Knead until very smooth. Stretch rather than roll to preserve the airy cornice (crust).</li>
      <li><strong>Fermentation:</strong> 24 to 48 hours cold ferment in the refrigerator for optimal flavor and chew.</li>
      <li><strong>Troubleshooting:</strong> If dough shrinks when stretching, cover it and let it rest 15 minutes to relax the gluten.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="recipe-section">
    <div class="recipe-header">
      <h3>2. Neapolitan</h3>
      <span class="recipe-meta">Bake: 800°F+ | Hydration: ~60%</span>
    </div>
    <p>A minimalist dough requiring a blazing hot oven to achieve a blistered, leopard-spotted crust and tender, airy texture.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Ingredients:</strong> Tipo 00 flour, water, salt, minimal yeast (fresh or active dry). No oil or sugar.</li>
      <li><strong>Technique:</strong> Gently stretch using the "slap and fold" technique, pushing air to the crust edges. Never use a rolling pin.</li>
      <li><strong>Fermentation:</strong> Ideally a 72-hour cold ferment. Let it come to room temperature for 2-3 hours before baking.</li>
      <li><strong>Troubleshooting:</strong> Dough tearing? Ensure you are using high-quality 00 flour and the dough has fermented long enough.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="recipe-section">
    <div class="recipe-header">
      <h3>3. Detroit Style</h3>
      <span class="recipe-meta">Bake: 500°F | Hydration: ~73%</span>
    </div>
    <p>Baked in a specialized rectangular steel pan. Yields a focaccia-like crumb, a crispy fried bottom, and caramelized cheese edges (frico).</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Ingredients:</strong> Bread flour, high water content, yeast, salt, olive oil (for the pan).</li>
      <li><strong>Technique:</strong> High-hydration dough pressed into an oiled 10x14 inch pan. Dimpled with fingers before topping.</li>
      <li><strong>Fermentation:</strong> 12-24 hours. A long proof directly in the pan is key to the airy texture.</li>
      <li><strong>Troubleshooting:</strong> If the crust isn't crispy, you may need more oil in the pan or a longer bake on the bottom oven rack.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="recipe-section">
    <div class="recipe-header">
      <h3>4. Sicilian</h3>
      <span class="recipe-meta">Bake: 425°F - 450°F | Hydration: ~65%</span>
    </div>
    <p>A thick, spongy, rectangular pan pizza. It’s hearty, robust, and often features the sauce layered beneath the cheese to prevent a soggy crust.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Ingredients:</strong> Bread flour or AP flour, water, yeast, salt, generous amounts of olive oil.</li>
      <li><strong>Technique:</strong> Spread gently into a heavily oiled baking sheet or pan. Needs a secondary proof in the pan before baking.</li>
      <li><strong>Fermentation:</strong> Typically 24 hours total, with the last 2-3 hours proofing at room temp in the oiled pan.</li>
      <li><strong>Troubleshooting:</strong> Dough won't stretch to the pan edges? Stretch it as far as you can, wait 20 minutes, then stretch again.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="recipe-section">
    <div class="recipe-header">
      <h3>5. Thin & Crispy (Tavern Style)</h3>
      <span class="recipe-meta">Bake: 450°F - 500°F | Hydration: ~48%</span>
    </div>
    <p>A Midwestern classic, cut into squares. Features an ultra-thin, cracker-like crust designed for heavy toppings and holding its shape.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Ingredients:</strong> All-purpose flour, water, salt, yeast, olive oil or vegetable shortening.</li>
      <li><strong>Technique:</strong> This is a very stiff dough. Use a rolling pin to roll it as thin as possible to eliminate large air pockets.</li>
      <li><strong>Fermentation:</strong> 24-72 hours in the fridge to hydrate the low-moisture dough.</li>
      <li><strong>Troubleshooting:</strong> If the crust is chewy instead of crispy, roll it thinner or bake slightly longer.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="recipe-section">
    <div class="recipe-header">
      <h3>6. Gluten-Free</h3>
      <span class="recipe-meta">Bake: 450°F - 500°F | Hydration: ~85%</span>
    </div>
    <p>A batter-like dough that relies on binders rather than gluten structure. Produces a surprisingly crisp crust when baked on a hot stone.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Ingredients:</strong> High-quality 1:1 GF flour blend (must contain xanthan gum), warm water, yeast, salt, olive oil.</li>
      <li><strong>Technique:</strong> Mix into a thick paste. Press out onto a piece of parchment paper using wet or oiled hands. Par-bake before adding toppings.</li>
      <li><strong>Fermentation:</strong> 1 to 2 hours at room temperature. GF dough does not benefit from long cold fermentation.</li>
      <li><strong>Troubleshooting:</strong> If the crust is gummy, ensure you par-bake the crust for 5-7 minutes before topping it.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>Essential Pizza Dough Knowledge</h2>

  <h3>Flour Comparison</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>00 Flour (Tipo 00):</strong> The finest Italian milling grade. Perfect for high-heat ovens (Neapolitan) as it lacks malted barley flour, preventing burning.</li>
    <li><strong>Bread Flour (12-14% Protein):</strong> High protein creates strong gluten development, ideal for chewy, airy New York style crusts in home ovens.</li>
    <li><strong>All-Purpose Flour (10-11% Protein):</strong> Versatile but lower in protein. Best for crispier, less chewy styles like Thin & Crispy or Sicilian.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Hydration Guide</h3>
  <p>Hydration refers to the water-to-flour ratio by weight (e.g., 650g water to 1000g flour = 65% hydration). Higher hydration yields lighter, airier crusts but is stickier and harder to handle. Lower hydration yields denser, sturdier, or crispier crusts.</p>

  <h3>Proper Stretching Technique</h3>
  <p>Never use a rolling pin unless making Thin & Crispy tavern style! A rolling pin crushes the air bubbles created by fermentation. Instead, gently press the dough out with your fingertips from the center, leaving a 1-inch border untouched for the crust. Then, use the back of your knuckles to gently stretch the dough by letting gravity pull it downward as you rotate it.</p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    {schema[1].mainEntity.map((faq) => (
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">{faq.name}</div>
        <div class="faq-a">{faq.acceptedAnswer.text}</div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>
</div>
